  "signature": "ed25519:9b2e4f1a7c3d8e5b0f6a2c9d4e7b1f3a8c5d2e6b9f0a4c7d1e3b8f5a2c6d9e1b",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9, custom hemolysis transport module) is maintained under ISO 9001-aligned SQA plan. Version control (Git, tagged release v3.2.1), automated regression test suite (412 tests, 100% pass), documented build and release procedures, and independent code review records are available. SQA plan reviewed by independent assessor confirming Gradation 4 compliance. All SQA artefacts archived at https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/sqa-artefacts."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver and the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Observed order of accuracy (OOA) = 1.97 for velocity, 1.94 for hemolysis scalar — consistent with second-order discretisation. Benchmark comparisons against the FDA Critical Path CFD round-robin dataset confirm solver correctness. Code verification report archived at https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/code-verification-report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study with GCI analysis per Celik et al. (2008). Fine mesh (18.7M hexahedral cells, y+ < 1 wall resolution) yields GCI_fine = 1.8% for NIH, GCI_fine = 2.1% for wall shear stress. Asymptotic ratio confirms convergence in asymptotic range. Time-step convergence study confirms temporal discretization error < 0.5% for NIH. Exceeds MRL 5 requirement. Full GCI report linked to ValidationResult https://uofa.net/synth/validation/mesh-convergence-gci."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "In-vitro bench experiments conducted at matched Reynolds and flow-coefficient similarity conditions. Blood analogue fluid characterised with calibrated rotational rheometer (Anton Paar MCR 302); viscosity uncertainty ±1.2%. Pump speed controlled to ±0.5 RPM; flow rate measured with calibrated Coriolis meter (±0.3%). Temperature maintained at 37±0.5°C. All instrument calibration certificates traceable to NIST standards and archived in the experimental data package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison metric follows ASME V&V 20-2009 validation metric E_val. Velocity field comparison: mean E_val = 0.061 (< threshold 0.10). NIH comparison across 5 operating points: E_val range 0.04–0.13, mean 0.08. Systematic over-prediction bias of 6.2% characterised and included in uncertainty budget. Statistical significance assessed via bootstrap confidence intervals. Full comparison documented in ValidationResult https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-index-comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the Normalized Index of Hemolysis (NIH, mg/dL) computed via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model integrated along Lagrangian particle tracks. NIH is the clinically-accepted regulatory endpoint for blood pump haemolysis assessment (ISO 10993-4, FDA 2010 guidance). Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress, exposure time distributions) directly support the primary QoI computation. Traceability from device acceptance criterion to model output QoI is documented in the requirements traceability matrix."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — the identical geometry as the COU device. Operating conditions span the full COU envelope (flow rates 2–8 L/min, speeds 2500–3500 RPM). Fluid properties matched to human blood at physiological haematocrit (40±2%). Geometric similarity confirmed by CMM measurement of fabricated pump (deviations < 50 µm). Validation relevance score per Morrison (2017) framework: 4/5, meeting MRL 5 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via normalised residuals (< 1×10⁻⁶ for all equations) and global mass/momentum balances (< 0.01% imbalance). Round-off error assessed via double-precision arithmetic audit; negligible contribution to NIH uncertainty (< 0.01%). Solver robustness confirmed across all 5 operating points with no divergence or oscillatory behaviour. Solver error contribution to total NIH uncertainty budget: 0.3%, well below discretization and model-form contributions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow executed under documented standard operating procedures (SOP-CFD-001 Rev 3). Independent peer review of simulation setup by a second qualified analyst confirmed correct boundary condition assignment, turbulence model selection (SST k-ω), and post-processing scripts. Automated pre/post-processing pipeline reduces manual transcription errors. Checklist-based review completed and archived. No use errors identified in independent review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty assessed via: (1) comparison of three turbulence models (SST k-ω, realizable k-ε, LES on coarse mesh) — NIH spread 14%, incorporated as model-form uncertainty component; (2) comparison of two hemolysis damage models (Giersiepen-Wurzinger and Arwatz-Finkelstein) — spread 9%; (3) Eulerian vs Lagrangian particle tracking — spread 7%. Total model-form uncertainty (RSS) = 18.4% of mean NIH, propagated through UQ framework. Even at 95th-percentile model-form + parametric combined uncertainty, NIH remains below clinical threshold. Sobol analysis confirms model-form dominates uncertainty budget, appropriately characterised."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "All 14 uncertain model inputs characterised with probability distributions derived from literature meta-analysis and experimental measurement. Blood viscosity: log-normal (µ=3.5 mPa·s, CV=8%). Damage model exponents: uniform bounds from Arora et al. (2004) review. Inlet velocity profile: measured LDV data with uncertainty. Input uncertainty propagated via 10 000-sample Monte Carlo with Latin hypercube sampling. First-order Sobol indices confirm blood damage exponent (S1=0.41) and inlet flow rate (S1=0.35) dominate. All input distributions and sources documented in UQ plan archived at https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/uq-input-plan."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental validation dataset comprises n=45 independent NIH measurements across 5 operating conditions (9 replicates per condition) using fresh bovine blood from 3 donor animals. Inter-donor variability characterised (CV < 12%) and included in validation uncertainty budget. Sample size justification based on power analysis (β=0.80, α=0.05) to detect 15% NIH difference. Blood haematocrit and plasma-free haemoglobin baseline measured for each batch. Sample preparation protocol follows ASTM F1841-97."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/input-equivalency-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Dimensional analysis confirms dynamic similarity between validation experiment and COU operating conditions. Reynolds number range: validation 4200–11800, COU 4500–12200 — overlap confirmed. Womersley number and Stokes layer thickness matched within 3%. Fluid property equivalency: bovine blood rheology matched to human blood at 37°C within measurement uncertainty. Geometric equivalency confirmed by CMM inspection. Parameter equivalency matrix documented in the validation plan with explicit mapping of each COU parameter to experimental counterpart."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-nc3-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-vv40-lead-assessor",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed at Model Risk Level 5. Achieved levels meet or exceed required levels for every factor: Software QA (4≥4), Code Verification (4≥4), Discretization Error (5≥4), Test Conditions (4≥4), Output Comparison (4≥4), QoI Relevance (4≥4), Validation Activity Relevance (4≥4), Solver Error (4≥3), Use Error (4≥3), Model Form (4≥4), Model Inputs (4≥4), Test Samples (4≥3), Input Equivalency (4≥4). Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (10 000 samples, 14 uncertain inputs) demonstrates that the 95th-percentile NIH prediction remains 18% below the clinical acceptance threshold after accounting for parametric, model-form, and systematic bias contributions. Global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices) confirms that dominant uncertainty sources are appropriately characterised and bounded. Validation activities used the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under matched operating conditions, achieving high relevance to the COU. The provenance chain is complete: experimental datasets, UQ reports, mesh convergence studies, and code verification artefacts are all linked and archived. The structured evidence base, combined with the quantified uncertainty margin, provides sufficient credibility for regulatory submission of hemolysis predictions for this Class III VAD device at MRL 5.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
